A Gothic Style space station. or Orbital Dock
This can be built a number of ways, with or without the arms. The join allows for extending to another platform (or to link 2 platforms).
At the end of the arms you can add the repair bay or a GW sized imperial broadside module. There is a couple on my profile to download as well.
The repair bay can be printed a second time and joined together to make a cage.

The platform is a free download if you want to check it out:
https://cults3d.com/en/3d-model/game/gothic-weapons-platform

Suitable in size and armament for a stand in for Imperial weapons platforms for the classic tabletop wargame Battlefleet Gothic. I've included two lance versions so you can have different models for long- and short-ranged versions (see BFG:XR).

I am not affiliated with GW in any way! Please don't reupload this on Shapeways and the like for commercial use (though you're welcome to upload them to get them printed that way for yourself).

2020-11-18 - Tweaked the short-ranged lance installation to have 4 turrets and also a lip on the turret towers so they look less "smushed". Thanks Molgrimmarr!

2020-11-20 Made the stabiliser widgets larger to make them print more reliably and be more robust. Again, thanks Molgrimmarr!

Created some space hulks to replace destroyed cap ships because it is always better to replace your enemies destroyed ship with smouldering wrecks!

Currently created Astartes, Chaos and Imperial wrecks, I will create other races as I print my way through the fleets!

I suggest printing these in the two halves supplied then smoothing the joint over with a hot finishing tool and you will not even see the joint ;)

print the smaller part flat side to bed with supports to build plate only and the larger part bottom down with supports to build plate only, any scarring will not be seen once mounted on the a base

**Update 12/03/20** Added wrecked Cruisers & Grand Cruisers...have fun!

Something I hobbled together in TinkerCad.

If you're going to print the sections of the dome separately, good luck lining them up, I believe in you. 

If you want to print the whole top dome as one piece, a setting that connects overhangs at various angles helps. I set mine to 45˚ (in the 'experimental' section of Cura 4.0), and as those overhangs are typically on the underside of a model, it doesn't detract too much from the look. (be aware that those settings on the lower half of the model will then have its "top" flat areas angled up at 45˚, such as the deck of the ring shaped structures around the narrowest part of the model.
